                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.711/27</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-17T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 17, 1917, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4710. Your 5988, April 13, 1 p.m. For <persName>Bell</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_HL1">Harrison</persName>: Many thanks valuable
                    information and excellent suggestion. Will make a point of seeing Major
                        <persName>Dansey</persName>. Appreciate War Office’s offer of
                    Worthington.</p>
                <p>So far no censorship here at all except wireless. Hoping to get approval
                    establish cable and land telegraph lines censorship. Considerable opposition
                    from many sources. Will keep you advised.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
